<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="92" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[113,753,1175,1615]" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,230,1175,1199]" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
By possessing a similar state of some characters (a bipartite thoracic fovea, relatively long and slender legs I–IV, a weakly swollen femur I, and a poorly developed leg scopula), the considered genus resembles members of 
<taxonomicName authority="Zonstein &amp; Marusik, 2013" authorityName="Zonstein &amp; Marusik" authorityYear="2013" box="[113,546,1303,1327]" class="Arachnida" family="Palpimanidae" genus="Levymanus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="92" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[113,235,1304,1327]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">Levymanus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Zonstein S &amp; Marusik YM" box="[245,546,1303,1327]" pageId="1" pageNumber="92" pagination="27 - 45" refId="ref5916" refString="Zonstein S &amp; Marusik YM (2013) On Levymanus, a remarkable new spider genus from Israel, with notes on the Chediminae (Araneae, Palpimanidae). ZooKeys, 326: 27 - 45." type="journal article" year="2013">Zonstein &amp; Marusik, 2013</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, distributed in the eastern part of Africa and in the Near East (
<figureCitation box="[609,746,1335,1359]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[136,171,1583,1605]" captionTargetBox="[136,1473,189,1568]" captionTargetId="figure-8@2.[136,1477,189,1570]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Scaled SEM micrographs of somatic structures of Boagrius pumilus (subadult female from Bukit Fraser, Malaysia). A, carapace, anterior view; B, thoracic fovea, dorsal; C, posterior notch of carapace; D–F, chelicera, anteroventral, ventral, and posteroventral view, respectively; G, H, palpal endites, ventral; I, palp, prolateral; J, leg I, tibia to tarsus, prolateral; K, apex of tarsus I, showing tarsal claws and tufts, anterior view; L, same, leg IV, retrolateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4577383" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4577383/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">Figs. 1B, 1J</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[113,125,1367,1391]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[113,148,1917,1939]" captionTargetBox="[113,1451,336,1902]" captionTargetId="figure-9@3.[113,1451,336,1902]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 2. A–D, habitus of Boagrius pumilus; E–H, habitus of B. simoni, new species; A, B, E, F, males; C, D, G, H, females; A, C, E, G, dorsal view; B, D, F, H, lateral view. Scale bar = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4577385" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4577385/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">2</figureCitation>
A–H cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="Zonstein S &amp; Marusik YM" box="[214,490,1367,1391]" pageId="1" pageNumber="92" pagination="27 - 45" refId="ref5916" refString="Zonstein S &amp; Marusik YM (2013) On Levymanus, a remarkable new spider genus from Israel, with notes on the Chediminae (Araneae, Palpimanidae). ZooKeys, 326: 27 - 45." type="journal article" year="2013">Zonstein &amp; Marusik, 2013</bibRefCitation>
: figs. 1, 2, 10, 11, 26–31). All other chedimine genera, except for those discussed here, embrace species possessing a pit-like or a slit-like thoracic fovea, a stouter femur I, and a better developed leg scopula (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Zonstein S &amp; Marusik YM" box="[165,454,1495,1519]" pageId="1" pageNumber="92" pagination="27 - 45" refId="ref5916" refString="Zonstein S &amp; Marusik YM (2013) On Levymanus, a remarkable new spider genus from Israel, with notes on the Chediminae (Araneae, Palpimanidae). ZooKeys, 326: 27 - 45." type="journal article" year="2013">Zonstein &amp; Marusik, 2013</bibRefCitation>
: figs. 1–9; 2017a: figs. 3–8, 11–15, 19, 40–42; 2017b: fig. 1A–E; 
<bibRefCitation author="Zonstein SL &amp; Marusik YM &amp; Omelko MM" box="[521,748,1527,1551]" pageId="1" pageNumber="92" pagination="93 - 103" refId="ref6074" refString="Zonstein SL, Marusik YM &amp; Omelko MM (2016) Redescription of the type species of Diaphorocellus Simon, 1893 (Araneae, Palpimanidae, Chediminae). African Invertebrates, 57: 93 - 103." type="journal article" year="2016">Zonstein et al., 2016</bibRefCitation>
: figs. 1–6; 2018: figs. 1–4; 
<bibRefCitation author="Zonstein SL &amp; Marusik YM &amp; Omelko MM" box="[402,694,1559,1583]" pageId="1" pageNumber="92" pagination="53 - 56" refId="ref6112" refString="Zonstein SL, Marusik YM &amp; Omelko MM (2018) Redescription of the monotypic genus Scelidomachus Pocock, 1899 (Aranei: Palpimanidae) and its type species. Arthropoda Selecta, 27: 53 - 56." type="journal article" year="2018">Marusik &amp; Zonstein, 2018</bibRefCitation>
: figs. 1–5, 12, 13).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[113,753,1655,2063]" lastBlockId="1.[813,1452,189,245]" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1893" box="[113,211,1656,1679]" class="Arachnida" family="Palpimanidae" genus="Boagrius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="92" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[113,211,1656,1679]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">Boagrius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be clearly distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zonstein &amp; Marusik" authorityYear="2013" box="[591,711,1656,1679]" class="Arachnida" family="Palpimanidae" genus="Levymanus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="92" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[591,711,1656,1679]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">Levymanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by: a) having a more compact cephalothorax with shorter and narrowed anterior and posterior parts; b) the presence of an elevated hump in the median part of the carapace; c) the relatively smaller AMEs (which are two to three times as large as other eyes); d) a shorter distance between the thoracic sulci; and e) a shorter abdomen with a considerably shorter petiolar tube (
<figureCitation box="[346,475,1879,1903]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[136,171,1583,1605]" captionTargetBox="[136,1473,189,1568]" captionTargetId="figure-8@2.[136,1477,189,1570]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Scaled SEM micrographs of somatic structures of Boagrius pumilus (subadult female from Bukit Fraser, Malaysia). A, carapace, anterior view; B, thoracic fovea, dorsal; C, posterior notch of carapace; D–F, chelicera, anteroventral, ventral, and posteroventral view, respectively; G, H, palpal endites, ventral; I, palp, prolateral; J, leg I, tibia to tarsus, prolateral; K, apex of tarsus I, showing tarsal claws and tufts, anterior view; L, same, leg IV, retrolateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4577383" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4577383/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">Figs. 1A, B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[488,501,1879,1903]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[113,148,1917,1939]" captionTargetBox="[113,1451,336,1902]" captionTargetId="figure-9@3.[113,1451,336,1902]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 2. A–D, habitus of Boagrius pumilus; E–H, habitus of B. simoni, new species; A, B, E, F, males; C, D, G, H, females; A, C, E, G, dorsal view; B, D, F, H, lateral view. Scale bar = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4577385" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4577385/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">2</figureCitation>
A–H, 3A–C, 3E–L). In species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zonstein &amp; Marusik" authorityYear="2013" box="[231,349,1912,1935]" class="Arachnida" family="Palpimanidae" genus="Levymanus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="92" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[231,349,1912,1935]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">Levymanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the carapace is longer and narrower anteriorly and posteriorly, the thoracic hump is not as conspicuous, the AMEs four to five times as large as other eyes, the distance between the thoracic sulci is noticeably broader, and the abdomen is longer with an unusually long petiolar tube (cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="Zonstein S &amp; Marusik YM" box="[1010,1309,189,213]" pageId="1" pageNumber="92" pagination="27 - 45" refId="ref5916" refString="Zonstein S &amp; Marusik YM (2013) On Levymanus, a remarkable new spider genus from Israel, with notes on the Chediminae (Araneae, Palpimanidae). ZooKeys, 326: 27 - 45." type="journal article" year="2013">Zonstein &amp; Marusik, 2013</bibRefCitation>
: figs. 10–15, 33–34; Zonstein et al., 2017: fig. 1A–F).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="93" pageId="1" pageNumber="92" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[812,1453,285,885]" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[813,954,285,309]" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">Description.</emphasis>
Small bicolour chedimine palpimanids with body length 
<quantity box="[941,1066,317,341]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.25" metricValueMax="2.4" metricValueMin="2.1" pageId="1" pageNumber="92" unit="mm" value="2.25" valueMax="2.4" valueMin="2.1">2.1–2.4 mm</quantity>
in males and 
<quantity box="[1207,1332,317,341]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.7" metricValueMax="2.8" metricValueMin="2.6" pageId="1" pageNumber="92" unit="mm" value="2.7" valueMax="2.8" valueMin="2.6">2.6–2.8 mm</quantity>
in females. Carapace domed and oval, slightly narrowed and truncated anteriorly and posteriorly, densely and finely corrugated (
<figureCitation captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[136,171,1583,1605]" captionTargetBox="[136,1473,189,1568]" captionTargetId="figure-8@2.[136,1477,189,1570]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Scaled SEM micrographs of somatic structures of Boagrius pumilus (subadult female from Bukit Fraser, Malaysia). A, carapace, anterior view; B, thoracic fovea, dorsal; C, posterior notch of carapace; D–F, chelicera, anteroventral, ventral, and posteroventral view, respectively; G, H, palpal endites, ventral; I, palp, prolateral; J, leg I, tibia to tarsus, prolateral; K, apex of tarsus I, showing tarsal claws and tufts, anterior view; L, same, leg IV, retrolateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4577383" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4577383/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
), with elevated hump between eye group and thoracic fovea. Eight eyes. AME largest, about two to three times larger than other eyes, which are subaequal in size. ALE and PLE almost touching each other. PME widely spaced from each other, as well as from AMEs and from PLEs. Clypeus about two times higher than AME diameter. Chilum inconspicuous. Thoracic fovea short and bipartite, with two separate sulci closely located side by side (
<figureCitation box="[1257,1337,637,661]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[136,171,1583,1605]" captionTargetBox="[136,1473,189,1568]" captionTargetId="figure-8@2.[136,1477,189,1570]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Scaled SEM micrographs of somatic structures of Boagrius pumilus (subadult female from Bukit Fraser, Malaysia). A, carapace, anterior view; B, thoracic fovea, dorsal; C, posterior notch of carapace; D–F, chelicera, anteroventral, ventral, and posteroventral view, respectively; G, H, palpal endites, ventral; I, palp, prolateral; J, leg I, tibia to tarsus, prolateral; K, apex of tarsus I, showing tarsal claws and tufts, anterior view; L, same, leg IV, retrolateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4577383" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4577383/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">Fig. 1B</figureCitation>
). Posterior notch deep subtriangular (
<figureCitation box="[1108,1197,669,693]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[136,171,1583,1605]" captionTargetBox="[136,1473,189,1568]" captionTargetId="figure-8@2.[136,1477,189,1570]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Scaled SEM micrographs of somatic structures of Boagrius pumilus (subadult female from Bukit Fraser, Malaysia). A, carapace, anterior view; B, thoracic fovea, dorsal; C, posterior notch of carapace; D–F, chelicera, anteroventral, ventral, and posteroventral view, respectively; G, H, palpal endites, ventral; I, palp, prolateral; J, leg I, tibia to tarsus, prolateral; K, apex of tarsus I, showing tarsal claws and tufts, anterior view; L, same, leg IV, retrolateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4577383" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4577383/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">Fig. 1C</figureCitation>
). Chelicerae relatively small, only slightly longer than clypeus; stridulatory ridges absent; cheliceral fang serrate; cheliceral furrow without true or peg teeth (
<figureCitation box="[1014,1076,765,789]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[136,171,1583,1605]" captionTargetBox="[136,1473,189,1568]" captionTargetId="figure-8@2.[136,1477,189,1570]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Scaled SEM micrographs of somatic structures of Boagrius pumilus (subadult female from Bukit Fraser, Malaysia). A, carapace, anterior view; B, thoracic fovea, dorsal; C, posterior notch of carapace; D–F, chelicera, anteroventral, ventral, and posteroventral view, respectively; G, H, palpal endites, ventral; I, palp, prolateral; J, leg I, tibia to tarsus, prolateral; K, apex of tarsus I, showing tarsal claws and tufts, anterior view; L, same, leg IV, retrolateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4577383" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4577383/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
D–F). Sternum shield-like, widest between coxae I and II, with fine reticulation; labium about as broad at base as it is long. Maxillae short and moderately wide (
<figureCitation box="[881,1004,861,885]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[136,171,1583,1605]" captionTargetBox="[136,1473,189,1568]" captionTargetId="figure-8@2.[136,1477,189,1570]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Scaled SEM micrographs of somatic structures of Boagrius pumilus (subadult female from Bukit Fraser, Malaysia). A, carapace, anterior view; B, thoracic fovea, dorsal; C, posterior notch of carapace; D–F, chelicera, anteroventral, ventral, and posteroventral view, respectively; G, H, palpal endites, ventral; I, palp, prolateral; J, leg I, tibia to tarsus, prolateral; K, apex of tarsus I, showing tarsal claws and tufts, anterior view; L, same, leg IV, retrolateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4577383" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4577383/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">Fig. 1G, H</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[813,1453,925,1173]" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">
Palps moderately short, with thickened distal segments in females (
<figureCitation box="[911,985,957,981]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[136,171,1583,1605]" captionTargetBox="[136,1473,189,1568]" captionTargetId="figure-8@2.[136,1477,189,1570]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Scaled SEM micrographs of somatic structures of Boagrius pumilus (subadult female from Bukit Fraser, Malaysia). A, carapace, anterior view; B, thoracic fovea, dorsal; C, posterior notch of carapace; D–F, chelicera, anteroventral, ventral, and posteroventral view, respectively; G, H, palpal endites, ventral; I, palp, prolateral; J, leg I, tibia to tarsus, prolateral; K, apex of tarsus I, showing tarsal claws and tufts, anterior view; L, same, leg IV, retrolateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4577383" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4577383/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">Fig. 1I</figureCitation>
); legs I–IV long and slender. Leg formula: 1423. Leg cuticula fairly smooth. Femur I rather long and weakly swollen; patella I thin and long (longer than tibia). Tibia and metatarsus I with weakly developed prolateral scopula (
<figureCitation box="[911,988,1085,1109]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[136,171,1583,1605]" captionTargetBox="[136,1473,189,1568]" captionTargetId="figure-8@2.[136,1477,189,1570]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Scaled SEM micrographs of somatic structures of Boagrius pumilus (subadult female from Bukit Fraser, Malaysia). A, carapace, anterior view; B, thoracic fovea, dorsal; C, posterior notch of carapace; D–F, chelicera, anteroventral, ventral, and posteroventral view, respectively; G, H, palpal endites, ventral; I, palp, prolateral; J, leg I, tibia to tarsus, prolateral; K, apex of tarsus I, showing tarsal claws and tufts, anterior view; L, same, leg IV, retrolateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4577383" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4577383/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">Fig. 1J</figureCitation>
). Leg tarsi straight (not curved), with two narrow unidentate claws and ascopulate (
<figureCitation box="[1258,1376,1117,1141]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[136,171,1583,1605]" captionTargetBox="[136,1473,189,1568]" captionTargetId="figure-8@2.[136,1477,189,1570]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Scaled SEM micrographs of somatic structures of Boagrius pumilus (subadult female from Bukit Fraser, Malaysia). A, carapace, anterior view; B, thoracic fovea, dorsal; C, posterior notch of carapace; D–F, chelicera, anteroventral, ventral, and posteroventral view, respectively; G, H, palpal endites, ventral; I, palp, prolateral; J, leg I, tibia to tarsus, prolateral; K, apex of tarsus I, showing tarsal claws and tufts, anterior view; L, same, leg IV, retrolateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4577383" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4577383/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">Fig. 1K, L</figureCitation>
). Claw tufts weakly developed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[812,1452,1213,1429]" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">Abdomen ovoidal, slightly extended anteriorly and obtuse posteriorly, without dorsal pattern (uniformly pale coloured) in unsclerotised part. Abdominal scuta conforming a rather short pedicel tube; dorsal portion of scutum relatively small. Small spinneret group set on low mound. AMS small, cylindrical, two-segmented; PMS and PLS reduced to a few sessile spigots in females and absent in males.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[812,1452,1469,1813]" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">
Male palp (
<figureCitation box="[941,1074,1469,1493]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[135,170,1876,1898]" captionTargetBox="[135,1474,346,1861]" captionTargetId="figure-8@4.[135,1474,346,1861]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 3. A–F, cephalothorax of Boagrius pumilus; G–I, cephalothorax of B. simoni, new species; A–D, G–I, males; E, F, J, K, females; A, E, G, J, dorsal view; B, F, H, K, ventral view; C, D, I, anterior part of cephalothorax in dorsal, ventral, and anterior view, respectively. Scale bar = 0.25 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4577387" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4577387/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">Figs. 3C, D</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1089,1102,1469,1493]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="5.[113,148,1951,1973]" captionTargetBox="[113,1451,300,1935]" captionTargetId="figure-9@5.[113,1451,300,1935]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Fig. 4. A–D, details of male palp of Boagrius pumilus; E–I, details of male palp of B. simoni, new species; A, E, entire palp, retrolateral; B, F, same, prolateral; C, D, G, distal part of palp, ventral; H, I, same, proventral. Scale bar = 0.25 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4577389" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4577389/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">4</figureCitation>
A–I, 5A–L). Femur longer than wide (ca. 2.3), equal in length to tibia and cymbium; patella more than two times shorter than femur; tibia strongly swollen, ca 1.6 thicker than femur; cymbium and bulb not embedded into the tibia; cymbium with sparse ‘scopular’ setae; bulb longer than cymbium, with two outgrowths, the tegular apophysis (
<emphasis box="[1014,1042,1662,1685]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">Ta</emphasis>
) and embolus (
<emphasis box="[1207,1243,1662,1685]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">Em</emphasis>
); tegular apophysis long (subequal to the length of tegulum), straight, with bent and bifurcated tip; embolus well sclerotised, relatively long (equal or ca. 1.5 times shorter than tegular apophysis), partly screwed (bent around the axis), with thin apophysis (
<emphasis box="[1394,1424,1790,1813]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">Ea</emphasis>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[813,1452,1853,2070]" lastBlockId="2.[136,775,1747,1835]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="93" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">
Female copulatory organ (
<figureCitation box="[1113,1181,1853,1877]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="8.[135,170,1947,1969]" captionTargetBox="[133,1471,277,1932]" captionTargetId="figure-8@8.[133,1471,277,1932]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Fig. 6. A, B, female copulatory organs of Boagrius pumilus; C–F, female copulatory organs of B. simoni, new species; A, endogyne, receptacles, and accessory structures, ventral view; B, D, same, posterior view; C, E, F, same, dorsal view.Scale bar = 0.25 mm. Abbreviations: At, atrium; Ft, fine thread; Gg, grape-shaped gland; Pg, pore gland; Rl, Rt, longitudinal and transversal parts of receptacle, respectively." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4577393" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4577393/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
A–F). Posterior edge of epigastric scutum bow-like, shallowly concave in median part, posterior edge of epigastric furrow (postgastric area) with two or three thin scuta, two lateral and one median (not distinct in 
<taxonomicName box="[982,1093,1981,2005]" class="Arachnida" family="Palpimanidae" genus="Boagrius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="92" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pumilis">
<emphasis box="[982,1093,1981,2005]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">B. pumilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), all these scuta almost invisible maceration. Endogynes differ in two species, wider than long (ca. 3 times in the 
<typeStatus box="[1072,1118,2046,2070]" pageId="1" pageNumber="92">type</typeStatus>
species and ca. 
<quantity box="[1296,1359,2045,2069]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.81" pageId="1" pageNumber="92" unit="in" value="1.5">1.5 in</quantity>
the new species); each receptacle (
<emphasis box="[435,459,1747,1771]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="93">Rl</emphasis>
+ 
<emphasis box="[495,519,1747,1770]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="93">Rt</emphasis>
) with three grape-like glands (
<emphasis box="[227,260,1779,1802]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="93">Gg</emphasis>
); receptacles in 
<typeStatus box="[450,497,1779,1803]" pageId="2" pageNumber="93">type</typeStatus>
species with pore gland field (
<emphasis box="[201,231,1811,1834]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="93">Pg</emphasis>
) anteriorly.
</paragraph>
